illegal sand mining over the past twenty years, ranging from Africa, Asia, and the Caribbean to South America and the eastern United States. They show how sand mining has reached crisis levels: beach, dune, and river ecosystems are in danger of being lost forever, while organized crime groups use deadly force to protect their illegal mining operations. Calling for immediate and widespread resistance to sand mining, the authors demonstrate that its cessation is paramount for saving not only beaches, dunes, and associated environments but also lives and tourism economies everywhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aNature. 7aNATURE / Ecosystems & Habitats / Coastal Regions & Shorelines.2bisacsh1 aHayes, Hannah L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLongo, Norma J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aNeal, William J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPilkey, Keith C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478092964zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478092964zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478092964/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA